<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Association Of Chief Police Officers (CMI0027)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Association Of Chief Police Officers </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(CMI0027)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In July 2011 the Association of British Insurers (ABI) and the City of London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Police announced the establishment of a dedicated police team to investigate UK based insurance fraud. The UK’s general insurance industry, through their trade body, agreed to commit £9 million funding to the unit over a three year period. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Known as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Insurance Fraud Enforcement Department (IFED), the 38-strong team of detectives and financial investigators act with operational independence whilst working closely with the insurance industry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although operationally independent, in its first two years o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f operation IFED has worked closely with the ABI and individual insurers to gain greater understanding of the threats regarding insurance fraud.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It was agreed at the inception of IFED that the unit would tackle general insurance fraud, estimated in 2011 t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o cost companies in excess of £2 billion per year. IFED would achieve this through robust enforcement activity and, at the same time, alter public perception that insurance fraud is in any way socially acceptable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The team’s key activities are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undertake enforcement and prevention activity based upon current threats, as agreed with the UK’s insurance sector.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To raise awareness of the harm caused by insurance fraud to the public and encourage them to report potential offenders to the police.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tackle organised crime groups and change the public perception that insurance fraud is a victimless crime.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Address high volume / low value crime thereby sending out a warning to opportunist criminals that the police will pursue a robust enforcement campai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gn against them.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To deny criminals access to criminal finances.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Collaborate with individual insurance businesses and the ABI’s Insurance Fraud Bureau to tackle insurance fraud.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In September 2013, Lloyd’s of London agreed an additional £200,000 per annu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m funding for IFED to investigate insurance fraud threats facing the UK’s wholesale insurance markets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Context</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED is currently tackling a range of long established criminality including motor insurance fraud, residential, commercial and public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">liability fraud. Additionally, IFED is focusing on emerging threats such as fraudsters selling fake car insurance (‘ghost broking’’).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst there are many thousands of suspected insurance fraud cases identified by the industry each year, the sheer volume</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of fraud attacks means that only a relatively small percentage of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cases are referred to IFED. The vast majority of fraud cases are detected by insurers companies and the claims repudiated. For this reason, a large part of IFED strategy involves prevention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> activity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of the referrals made to IFED by the insurance industry, the issue of the ‘crash for cash’ offences has been a significant area of concern. The annual cost of this category has been estimated at £392 million per annum. Since IFED only deals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with a limited proportion of identified cases, it is difficult to provide any clarification on this figure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">From its inception, IFED has investigated 94 separate crash for cash cases, which is by far the single largest insurance fraud type the unit encoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ters.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The vast majority of these investigations include claims for minor soft tissue injuries which are allegedly sustained as a consequence of the reported incident. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of these 94 referrals, 17 offenders have been convicted at court and 64 have received </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">police cautions.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arrests and convictions are publicised through mainstream and social media to maximise opportunities for enforcing the message of prosecution and prevention.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">34 cases remain live with arrests pending in the near future. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have noted three distinct types of crash for cash scam. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The first is the ‘staged’ accident where two vehicles, both in possession of the criminals, are deliberately crashed together away from public view. Sometimes fraudsters will simply take a sledg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e hammer to the bodywork in an effort to replicate the effects of a genuine car crash.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The second is the ‘induced' accident or ‘slam on’. This is where the fraudster targets an innocent motorist to become the at fault driver. Typically the fraudster’s car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will pull in front of the victim, slam on the brakes and – if the driver can’t stop in time be shunted from the rear. We have seen methods becoming more sophisticated over time, with a second decoy vehicle involved, fake witnesses and the recent advent of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘flash for cash’ where the fraudster will invite the innocent motorist to make a manoeuvre and then crash into them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The third is s the ‘ghost’ accident which is essentially a paper based fraud which involves submitting completely fabricated claims for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ccidents which actually never took place.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED prioritises the ‘slam on type’ as this causes genuine risk of physical injury to unsuspecting road users.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED uses all investigative tactics including covert operations designed to target active crash for c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ash organised crime groups.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suspected fraudulent claims are also detected using a number of different  investigation tools including:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCTV of the collision that indicates the crash is either contrived induced or exaggerated in terms of severity or number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of passengers. ANPR is also used to determine if the vehicle was in the location vicinity at the time of the accident.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Expert crash engineers examine the vehicle to determine if the damage is consistent with the claim report.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claims are cross checked fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r evidence of falsified medical records. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cross industry checks with insurers to determine if frequent claims by the same policy holder to identify other common factors such as passengers, contact details, mobile numbers or email addresses. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Post inciden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t surveillance and witness evidence to establish if the level of injury is consistent with the medical claim i.e. incapacity, mobility.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is worth noting that IFED has seen, in the worst case scenarios, slam-on-collisions that involve not only claims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for whiplash (including bogus passenger claims) but also for vehicle damage, loss of earnings, vehicle recovery, replacement car hire and vehicle storage. The total can exceed £30,000 for one such incident.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Organised crime groups often have close links w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ith professional enablers including: car replacement companies; car repair body shops; motor engineers; doctors and solicitors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although IFED has made arrests across England and Wales, it is apparent that offences are more prevalent in certain areas of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The hotspots encountered are London, Manchester, Liverpool, West Yorkshire, West Midlands and South Wales.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fraudulent motor insurance injury claims fall into two general categories – opportunistic and organised claims.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Opportunistic claims are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">generally instances where an accident has occurred however the level of injury is exaggerated from very minor discomfort with no effects felt shortly after the incident up to claims for longer lasting injury, soft tissue damage and the inability to work fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r a number of weeks. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012 a landmark prison sentence was handed out to a crash for cash conspirator. The seven year and three month jail term sent a clear statement from our justice system that insurance fraud will not be tolerated.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED has observed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that insurance companies deal with whiplash claims without a common standard. There are some companies that will issue payouts without requiring any medical evidence (known as ‘pre-med’ payments). This business decision does not help to weed out any fraud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sters who may be uncomfortable about faking an injury to a medical examiner.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The unit has seen evidence of organised crime groups, often using claims management companies to handle their claims, instruct the same medical organisations to evidence the level of injury sustained by the claimants. The medical organisations are also ope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rating as a profit based company and are naturally seeking repeat business. Whiplash injuries are notoriously difficult to disprove on medical examination, which leaves this area ripe for exploitation by unscrupulous enablers. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In some cases, claims management companies also own the sister company of the medical reporting organisation. These financial links are of concern to the police when considering medical independence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our operational activity has enabled us to learn that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some fraudulent claimants are aware of the difficulties the insurance industry face when investigating claims. Many fraudulent claimants will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">try to pitch the claim value at the right level so as to avoid closer scrutiny from the insurer. Therefore in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">case of a reported medical condition such as low level whiplash (which would have naturally healed by the time the claimant has been referred for medical examination), the insurance industry struggles to obtain evidence that may negate such a claim. This i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s why changes in legislation may assist to reduce the volume of fraudulent whiplash claims.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED has produced the first ever intelligence threat assessment for the insurance industry which is fed into by the NFIB and IFB along with numerous insurers. It i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s this document which drives the unit’s operational plan, directly targeting crime types which the industry inform police are threatening them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prior to the formation of IFED, ABI research indicated that dishonest claimants considered insurance fraud to b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a low risk offence. They expected to be either paid by the insurance company, or at worst for the claim to be repudiated with no further action.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IFED has introduced the very real possibility that insurance fraudsters will be investigated, arrested </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and prosecuted. This is acting as a deterrent and making insurance fraud a less attractive proposition. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>